<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph box="[968,1878,914,1235]" pageId="13" pageNumber="266" type="mainText">Small herbs. Leaves alternate. Flowers in clusters, these axillary or in spiciform intlorescences; perianth lobes 2-4, free or connate at the base, hooded; stamen 1; disk wanting; ovary unilocular. Pericarp diaphanous, i free from the seed coat; embryo slightly hooked, subannular; seeds vertical or horizontal. About 17 spp., mostly Australia, New Zealand.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph box="[970,1877,1242,1421]" pageId="13" pageNumber="266" type="mainText">
This genus, sometimes placed into a separate family, has proved to be a near relative of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="266" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Chenopodium</taxonomicName>
, several species of which have a very similar floral morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
